description.plain:
Adrianne Lenker’s “anything” came as a surprise on September 2, 2020, just a little under a year since her last major release in 2019 with Big Thief on Two Hands. The song was released simulatenously with the album announcement as the first of eleven tracks on the album.

“anything” does not sound far off from the rest of Big Thief’s work—it carries the same enchanting vocals and tender lyrics—but is especially similar to Lenker’s previous solo works, which are more folk-infused and sparse in instrumentation.

annotations:
Mango in your mouth, juice drippin’
 Shoulder of your shirt sleeve slippin’

Lenker is describing the small moments that she observed and loved while with her now ex-wife Indigo Sparke. Lines like these are scattered throughout the entire song and are meant to convey Lenker’s deep love for the small parts of the relationship, even when it seemed to be headed south.

Weren’t we the stars in Heaven
 Weren’t we the salt in the sea

Adraianne is relving the relationship in fond light. Saying they were ‘the stars in heaven,the salt in the sea’ they were perfection,they were greatness,they were needed to make great things great. But shes asking this because the relationship slipped away,the great thing ended so shes needs to be validated and reminded that it was something amazing but is also wondering if it was so brilliant why did it end.

Listen to your heart beating
 Listen to the way you move

adrianne wants to be closer to her partner and gain this level of intamicy which is impossible to have with someone she wants to know everything about and understand them on a deeper level leaving nothing for the imagination to dream up or desire just for her to know.

Wanna listen to the sound of you blinking
 Wanna listen to your hands soothe
adrianne wants to do more than just love her lover–she wants to get so intimate as to listen to the tiniest sounds her lover makes, down to the noise her blinking or her hands soothing her.
Carol has a little if we need some
adrianne is most likely referring to weed here, by “some”, if things get too stressful and they need to calm down.

Dragon in the new warm mountain
 Didn’t you believe in me?

Adrianne drops a hint at the title of the next Big Thief record.

https://genius.com/albums/Big-thief/Dragon-new-warm-mountain-i-believe-in-you

Fan on the ceiling like a wheel spoke
 Push the clutch and I pull the choke

The first line of this couplet evokes imagery of laying down and staring at the ceiling, could also be touching on how you might lay in bed underneath the ceiling fan with a lover
the second line mentions pushing the clutch of a manual transmission, pulling the choke to start it, which could be a reference to how Adrienne drove a rinky-dink old truck across the country with a trailer full of her life in it, mentioned in the KEXP at home interview, how she drove (very) slowly across the U.S. in it, which also ties back to the first line of the “wheel spoke” that is the ceiling fan.

Christmas Eve with your mother and sis
 Don’t wanna fight but your mother insists

Adrienne spent christmas eve with her ex-lover’s mother and sister, as spouses tend to, recalling how she tried not to instigate a fight between her and her lover, but her mother insisted upon an issue that may have seemed like a problem she could’ve sidestepped, but her girlfriend’s mother escalated (potentially unknowingly) the spat into something more explosive, which is a stark contrast to the last stanza in which Adrienne recalled the sensual and intimate moments she shared with Indigo Sparke – her former lover.
Dog’s white teeth slice right through my fist

A dog (specifically a black dog) is often used as a symbol for depression. The dog in this line may not be literal, but may instead represent the depressed Lenker, who is cutting herself – but that depressed self is externalized/separated here from the narrating Lenker, who is “bit” but does not explicitly cut herself.

Staring down the barrel of the hot sun
 Shining with the sheen of a shotgun (shotgun)

“Staring down the barrel” evokes imagery of a gun, but the end of the line quickly drops that expectation. Immediately afterwards, “Shining with the sheen of a shotgun” abruptly (and now unexpectedly) brings that imagery back. It’s an interesting change-up.

It’s also a foreboding image or omen. The relationship ended.
Facing your loneliest moments can also feel like staring down a black void. And when you well and truly miss someone, it can physically hurt.

annotations: You know me

The lyrics should be
“You know me new,
Knew me well”

Meaning Johnathan knows her now as her younger (19 year old) self when she was ‘new’. Which could mean new in love, new in life, new sexually, etc.  How you know and remember someone can be wrong if you don’t know how they’ve grown and changed over the years. These lyrics allude to a lot of time and distance between the singer and Johnathan. He knew her well, but not anymore. There is a nostalgia for the past and the intimacy there was back then

This is not the effect
 Of a loss, or a vex
 This is you
The speaker in emotional shambles. In a state that resembles grief for losing a loved one but is in fact over a lover.
You don’t know me now

A response to the previous verse where she places “know” in the past tense to illustrate the amount of time that’s passed and how she’s changed. This is a bold statement given her indecision in the last verse. This shows the fragility of their relationship and how quickly nostalgia can fade to reveal that people change.

Knew, knew me well
 When I was just a girl, only nineteen

This acts as an interruption to a train of thought, she had assumed that because they were very close when she was 19 and “twisted in [her] head” that relationship would translate now that she’s an adult. But this is disputed in the next verse.

annotations: As the wren bares her feathers

similar to the line ‘as the wren sheds her feathers’ adrianne is talking about the fact that wrens shed their feathers very often and dont bare them for long periods of time so shes aware the relationship wont last forever

As the wren sheds her feather
 Not a lot, just forever

The ‘wren shedding its feathers’ shows its growing up, it could be to reference that as we grow up we lose people memories and parts of ourselves and we will continue to do this throughout our entire lives ‘not a lot just forever’. However, she could be saying that though she will lose parts of her life as tine goes in she never wants to ‘shed’ him, he’s not a feather he’s something far more crucial to the bird.
The ‘not a lot just forver’ could be refrencing how in relationships people often feel that they are asking for too much so she makes sure to say that its not a lot and down plays it but really forever is a really long time and she knows that but she would never ask too muuh of him because shes scared to lose him.

And I wanna be your wife
 So I hold you to my knife
 And I steal your letter

Despite knowing the other person is not good to her, she tries to save the crumbling relationship using whatever charm she has left. She views it as a weapon—a powerful juxtaposition—her smile, kindness or sense of humor compared to the edge of a blade.

In this context, ‘letter’ may act as a synecdoche for the other person’s last name. Through marriage she would take on the other person’s last name as her own.

Not a lot, just forever
 Intertwined sewn together
 Like the rock bears the weather
 Not a lot, just forever

While “like the rock bears the weather” is a clear image of “not a lot, just forever,” it’s a strange image to use given the idea of being “intertwined, sewn together” with somebody. A rock is slowly worn down over time, but we might typically think of marriage as making people whole. Maybe it’s getting at the friction mentioned in later verses, such as Verse 4:

So I bash around the house
And the poison stains my mouth

The guitar and soft voice give the chorus a very sweet love-song sorta feel. But the lyrics suggest a bleakness underneath.
She comes, I let her

The passivity in this line is an interesting contrast to the violent agency she expresses in Verse 3 when talking about her relationship. While is seems like the marriage happens through her force of will, the child comes of its own accord, only needing acquiescence.

And we share a paradise
 And I roll them once or twice

Clever pun playing on the homophony of “paradise” and “pair of dice”.

In a song preoccupied with childbearing, the paradise/pair of dice pun could illuminate two facets of lovemaking: it’s both wonderful (paradise) and bears the possibility of conception (pair of dice).

My dog barks wildly
 To protect my infancy
 From my ex-believer
 And I try to calm the wolf
 To remind her I am both
 Still she tears at my sweater

The wolf in “not a lot, just forever” parallels the wolf in “Wolf” on Big Thief’s record Two Hands:

My safekeeper
The wolf is howling for me

In both songs, the wolf protects the speaker from a partner who is distant and emotionally abusive. Additionally, in both songs, the speaker tries to rationalize the abuse: in “not a lot, just forever,” the speaker insists that she is also manipulative, and in “Wolf,” she vows to return to the partner even after being discarded by her.

In “From” (included on both Big Thief’s U.F.O.F. and Adrianne Lenker’s abysskiss), Lenker also sings about a dog’s protection:

One ear to the ground
One dog at my neck
One tongue to my tongue
Wanting to protect me from

annotations:
We’re standing at the end of a story
 At the foot of a palindrome

A palindrome is a word that is the same spelled forwards and backwards. If the last word in the story is a palindrome, the whole story might be one too – endlessly repeating over and over again. In this case, the ‘story’ likely refers to adrianne’s touring life.
Come on my combat chameleon give it up

Potentially a play on Culture Club’s “Karma Chameleon,” in which the chorus goes “Karma Karma Karma Karma Karma Chameleon.” https://genius.com/5085830 She could be referring to a misunderstanding of these lyrics she had when she was a child. The speaker is probably her father as in the first stanza who might be poking at her childish misunderstanding of these lyrics? A guess on an admittedly obscure lyric.

One shot honey collect it all
 The dust inside the rusted souls

This lyric seems to navigate the bittersweetness of the touring, musical life contemplated in the first stanza. “One shot honey collect it all” leads you to expect glamour and fame—like you’re collecting large amounts of money or prestige. But in the next line we see what she’s collecting—"the dust inside the rusted souls."

Daddy wanted me to leave it
 Indiana, Indiana in the cold

“Lenker was born into a cult in Indiana that her parents left when she was young.” Her parents also seemed to have pushed her out the door a bit toward a career in music. “Leave it” could refer to leaving the cult, or maybe leaving home for music.

description.plain:
For GQ, Lenker said:
Ingydar was the name of my great-aunt Becky’s horse, who passed away when I was a kid. But the song itself, I have to say, it isn’t really about that horse. That was just a fragment from the pool of ideas, or colors that I wove into the song, but yeah. “Everything eats and is eaten / Time is fed.” Have you ever used a vacuum cleaner, and there’s a button that sucks the cord back in?

I imagine life being like the cord, and just being sucked back into the mouth of time, or that time is built up of experience in life. I suppose this is a pretty common thing to think about and philosophize about, but just looking at it as nonlinear, and as like a big orb or sphere, or maybe shapeless, but not with a before and an after and like a linear trajectory, but actually cyclical. Everything is constantly being born and decaying simultaneously. We’re both growing and becoming, and also unbecoming and decaying simultaneously. It’s like there’s this inherent duality within everything. I was going through a transition in a relationship at the time that was so painful and still is, but that feeling of our relationship just being eaten, or the idea of like, whatever state we’re in now, me and this person that were in this relationship, it’s our relationship, and all the journey and processing we had to go through was the sacrifice for our new state of being. And it was eaten by time.

annotations:
The juice of dark cherries cover my skin
 Six years in, no baby

This lyric alludes to Lenker’s relationship with ex-husband Buck Meek, whom she was with for six years. Lenker has spoken about how they thought of having children together. Because the “juice of dark cherries” is a metaphor for death, Lenker is making a comparison between the ending of relationships and death.

His eyes are blueberries, video screens, Minneapolis schemes
 And the dried flowers from books half-read
 The juice of dark cherries cover his chin
 The dog walks in and the crow lies in his jaw like lead

Adrianne uses this imagery to highlight the unpredictable and relentless nature of life and death, relating the sudden death of her great-aunt Becky’s horse Ingydar to a book you never finished. The flower marks the last page you read, like the cherry colored blood of the horse marks the end of her life. At any moment you might just decide to put the book down, even if it was a good read. Life is too unpredictable to be certain you will finish the story.

Everything eats and is eaten
 Time is fed

There is a cycle, a seasonality to all of nature – life and death, planting and harvesting, eating and being eaten. Time is marked by the rotation of this cycle and passage of these seasons. We are inescapably embedded in this system. We eat now and we will be eaten in a time to come.

body.plain: It appears that Adrianne is recalling an episode of sleep paralysis in which she experienced a hallucination of a zombie girl and she wishes to feel her, kiss her, and understand her more. This could also be a self reflection as she may realize that this hallucination is a manifestation of her thoughts and she is perplexed by her own mind.

annotations: What’s on your mind?
An invitation to the personified feeling of Emptiness to open up to her. Or, perhaps, a rhetorical question to herself.
Vacant as a closed down fair

Apt metaphor: the party’s over, no one there, lifeless, empty; “emptiness,” the narrator will say soon enough.  But the antecedent for “vacant” could also be the narrator.  Yes, the zombie girl is vacant—as zombies are, all body, no soul, no psyche, just hunger and lurch—but the risk of being with or even near the zombie girl is vacancy itself: “I,” frozen as I am, will be emptied out, vacant.
Sleep paralysis

The narrator isn’t only describing the zombie girl; the narrator too is affected: “frozen in bed,” paralyzed.  So, the song isn’t only about an encounter in this “almost” dream with a zombie; the song also shows how zombies proliferate: zombies create zombies create zombies…

I cover you with questions
 Cover you with explanations

Here Adrianne may be referencing over communication. In relationships one partner may try to draw too much out of the other leaving them feeling emotionally drained. Adrianne would thus be covering their partner with questions and trying to account for their inability to answer them through covering them with explanations; trying to use her own vocabulary to explain her partners emotions for them

I sworn I could’ve felt you there
 And I almost could’ve kissed your hair

She is talking about the zombie girl that she saw during her episode of sleep paralysis.

At this point, it is important to point out the use of the word zombie. Zombies are described as living dead. Someone who has passed away but keeps on living.

Adrianne saw someone that she knew to be dead, but she understands that what she saw wasn’t real. She thought fondly of this person and wishes that she could kiss them on the head one last time.

What a dream that was
 I almost couldn’t wake because
 I was frozen in bed with a zombie girl

Adrianne recalls an episode of sleep paralysis, which leaves a person immobile for a minute or two upon waking.

Some people also experience hallucinations during sleep paralysis. These could be fragments from dreams that the person was experiencing while they were sleeping. This could explain why Adrianne saw a “zombie girl” in her bed.

Oh, emptiness
 Tell me ’bout your nature
 Maybe I’ve been getting you wrong

In an interview with The New Yorker, Lenker
spoke about this line:

‘Emptiness / Tell me about your nature.’ That’s a real question. I want to understand—what is this feeling of emptiness? Is that me? Am I just hollow and empty? Or is emptiness actually something beautiful?

Whenever there is a void, it is human nature to want to fill it with something. It feels wrong for there to be a space, a moment where there is nothing. Maybe emptiness is misunderstand, and it is not just a lack of something.

album.full_title: Hours Were the Birds by Adrianne Lenker
album.name: Hours Were the Birds

annotations: Still, every night, I call you on the phone
The loss that the singer experienced motivates them to keep going. In other words, the loss the singer experienced is the engine that keeps their steamboat going.

And one day I’mma be a steamboat baby
 One day I can be your freight train lady
 I roll down the river, and the miles won’t phase me
 Oh, I wish I was better at being alone

The guitar strumming at this point, rhythmic and repeated. However, one note starts to become seemingly out of tune. Strange and unreal, the feeling of the song reveals its true form. The singer starts to discuss limited time. It sounds like the singer has experienced some kind of loss. The song begins to become more powerful, the guitar volume increases. In the end, the singer longs to see someone that they miss. It seems that they cannot deal with the despair that results from loneliness. They will travel any distance just to be with the person again. To conclude, the singer is trying to cope with the loss they have experienced. I think that at some point in their life they experienced some broken trust. They want to someday be able to rely on someone. A steamboat relies on steam to move which is why the artist used it.

Well, I’m just a stranger, I’m only a walker
 I guess I am human, but sometimes I feel
 Like I’m only a ghost, like I’m only a wall

Lenker feels as though she has no sense of identity or direction outside of her relationships with others. She doesn’t know what to do unless she has someone to follow around or be there for her.

Her lack of esteem and absence of a sense of identity makes her feel like she'’s sort of haunting people by hovering around them like a ghost. She feels a bit invisible.

And one day I’mma be a steamboat baby
 One day I can be your freight train lady
 I roll down the river and the miles won’t phase me

one day, she’s going to grow strong enough within her sense of self that she wont have to depend on others. Then, she can be a support for someone else to depend on.

She is implying that in her current state of mind, she can’t just roll down the river and enjoy life. She’s in a constant state of distress due to the fact that she needs companionship to feel safe and valid as a person.

And if you come around, honey
 I’ll probably just follow you home
 ’Cause it’s all that I know how to do
She’s not sure how to act in relationships, because she is so afraid of being lonely that she will do anything to receive affection and company.

I was born by a body, I’ll die by one too
 And places are nothing if they ain’t got you
She is so afraid to die alone that she is codependent on her relationships for happiness. She can’t be content anywhere unless it is with someone.

Yeah, I wonder what remains

This could be an implication that Kerina is away on some sort of journey past borders. This is probably why the speaker feels worried enough to be calling her all of the time.

“losing the line” could mean that she keeps losing connection with Kerina over the phone. She’s worried about her, either because she wants confirmation that she cares about her, or Kerina is somewhere unsafe and is worried about her whereabouts. Nonetheless, Kerina keeps reassuring her that everything is going to be okay.

In her song, ‘Steamboat’ from hours were the birds, Adrianne sings,

As stated before, she has a difficult time being alone and wants this relationship to be closer than it is. She is constantly making contact with someone over the phone, and is waiting for some sort of sign. Possibly some type of indication that Kerina has mutual feelings for her.

song.title: ​two reverse

annotations: Grandmother, Juniper
a combination of maternal/ familial love and romantic love is explored in the song, possibly a message in how people turn to their family for love after the ‘two rivers reverse’ and loved ones split

Light blue, dark blue, grey
 Crimson trail
 Straight through, stay don’t stray
I interpret this as the singer’s description of the conjoined river of the two lovers – it reflects different colors in the dawn and at dusk and she wants it to stay as it is.

To my home, two rivers
 Through my home, two reverse

We know this album is inspired by the end of Lenker’s relationship with her girlfriend. Given that, I read the ‘two rivers’ as the two of them coming together to form a home. But then the two rivers reverse at some point and move away from each other.

Light blue, dark blue, grey
 Crimson trail
 Straight through, stay don’t stray

In constrast with the shade of the colors, first light, then dark we can say this could be the intensity of sadness and dependence until we get grey some isolated and indifference feeling, like she got drained her energy off from this catarsis to the crimson trail. In literature crimson has been represented as strenght or power.

Also if we take a look of the cover of the album this has a stronger meaning  (the flowers).

Crimson in flowers language we can find the concepts like  “crimson polyanthus” which represents “the mystery of the heart”, while a deep crimson rose represents mourning.

description.plain:
Adrianne explained the meaning behind ‘symbol’ at a press release prior to the album’s release…

“While I was resting for a week between tours, ‘symbol’ came through,” she says. “I think it was born out of the feeling of wanting to feel at home somewhere amidst the blur of constant travel.

“Writing it helped me articulate the recognition of a very deep sense of home contained within the warmth of my loved ones and friends made visible in something as simple as a smile.”

annotations:
Do you see circling through?
 That’s how one returns from two
Perhaps she is referring to the circling of hands around a clock. In a repeating, circular sequence, two o' clock will eventually find it’s way back to one o' clock.
Fly make flea, make haste, make waste, eight makes infinity
Although absurd in terms of quantity, if you turn a figure eight on its side, it is exactly the same as an infinity symbol.
